# DEVOS — Enhanced Product & Implementation Brief

**Prepared by:** Senior Product Strategist & Solutions Architect
**Date:** 4 March 2026
**Inputs:** DEVOS PRD v1.2 · DEVOS Implementation Plan v1.0

---

## 1. Product Summary

DEVOS is a multi-tenant, AI-powered operating system for off-plan real estate developers in Nigeria and West Africa. It replaces the fragmented stack of sales agents, financial controllers, ad managers, and project coordinators with three integrated modules — **PRESELL** (autonomous lead-to-sale pipeline via WhatsApp + paid ads), **GUARDIAN** (AI budget watchdog that catches overcharges before payment), and **COMMAND** (a single-screen daily dashboard). The developer spends 15–20 minutes per day reviewing a morning brief, approving flagged invoices, and taking hot-lead calls. Everything else runs autonomously via a purpose-built Claude-powered agent system with per-organisation data isolation. Built first on Primerose Smart City Cluster (200-unit development, Rivers State), DEVOS is architected as SaaS from Sprint 1 and targets three paying external clients within six months.

---

## 2. What's Strong — Keep As Is

These are the parts both documents got right. Do not second-guess them.

| # | What's Strong | Source |
|---|--------------|--------|
| 1 | **Multi-tenant from Sprint 1.** Shared DB + `organisation_id` on every table + RLS is the correct call. The PRD's rationale for why separate instances per client is wrong is airtight. | PRD §5.1 |
| 2 | **DEVOS Agent Engine ≠ OpenClaw.** The PRD draws a hard, clean line. The agent engine is a product component; OpenClaw is a private tool with read-only access. This distinction protects the product's independence. | PRD §4.1, §5.6 |
| 3 | **Edge Functions replace n8n entirely.** Correct decision. Removes a runtime dependency, keeps deterministic routing fast and cheap, and limits AI costs to tasks that actually need reasoning. | PRD §4.1 |
| 4 | **Per-client credential injection via Supabase Vault.** One MCP infrastructure, per-org credentials at call time. Scalable and secure. | PRD §4.4 |
| 5 | **Agent permission boundaries (CAN / CANNOT table).** The PRD's explicit table of what the agent can and cannot do autonomously is one of the strongest parts of the entire document. It removes ambiguity for both developers and users. | PRD §4.4 |
| 6 | **Phased build order in the plan.** Phase 1 delivers lead capture, Phase 2 adds financial controls, Phase 3 adds intelligence. This is the right sequence — you ship revenue-generating capability first. | Plan §Phases |
| 7 | **Evidence-gated invoice submission.** The Contractor Portal physically blocks submission until all photos and certificates are uploaded. This is the single most important fraud-prevention control in the system. | PRD §6.4 |
| 8 | **Payment Ticket as the only path to outbound payment.** No Payment Ticket, no payment. Simple, auditable, enforceable. | PRD §6.5 |
| 9 | **Lead scoring algorithm with concrete point values.** Testable, tunable, transparent. Much better than vague "AI decides." | PRD §5.2.2 |
| 10 | **WhatsApp qualification flow states.** The 9-state machine (INTAKE → DEAD) is well-defined and covers the real-world funnel. | PRD §5.2.3 |
| 11 | **Agent hand-off specifications in the plan.** Clear delineation of who (Frontend Agent, Backend Agent, AI Agent Developer, MCP Developer) owns each task. This is essential for parallel workstreams. | Plan §Hand-offs |
| 12 | **Acceptance criteria per phase.** Each phase has measurable, testable exit criteria. This prevents scope drift. | Plan §Phase 1–3 |

---

## 3. Gaps in the PRD

Requirements that were vague, missing, or underspecified. Each gap includes the requirement as it should have been written.

### 3.1 Missing: Finance View

The PRD lists "Finance View — Payment ticket queue, outbound payment confirmation" in the Presentation Layer but never specifies its components, permissions, or workflow.

> **Corrected Requirement:** The Finance View shall display all Payment Tickets in status PENDING, grouped by urgency. For each ticket, it shall show: contractor name, amount, approval reference, approver name, approval timestamp, and a button to mark as PAID with required fields: bank reference number, payment date, and optional screenshot upload. Only users with role `finance` within the organisation shall access this view. Marking a ticket as PAID shall trigger `on-payment-confirmed` and update the GUARDIAN budget dashboard in real time.

### 3.2 Missing: Site Manager Progress Submission

The PRD mentions the Site Manager submits progress updates and purchase requests, but never defines the interface or data model for progress submissions.

> **Corrected Requirement:** The Site Manager View shall include a "Submit Progress Update" form with fields: phase (dropdown from project phases), percent complete (numeric, 0–100), written summary (text, required, min 50 chars), and photo uploads (minimum 3 photos, geotagged if device supports it). On submission, the `on-progress-update` Edge Function fires, updates the Buyer Portal construction progress bars, and cross-references against any pending invoices claiming work on the same phase. A new `progress_updates` row is created with `organisation_id`, `project_id`, `phase_id`, `reported_by`, `percent_complete`, `summary`, `photo_urls[]`, and `submitted_at`.

### 3.3 Missing: Payment Schedule Data Model

The PRD describes payment plans extensively (reminder sequences, overdue escalation, buyer portal payment tracker) but never defines the underlying `payment_schedule` table.

> **Corrected Requirement:** A `payment_schedule` table shall exist with columns: `id`, `organisation_id`, `buyer_id`, `reservation_id`, `instalment_number`, `amount`, `currency`, `due_date`, `status` (PENDING | PAID | OVERDUE | DEFAULTED), `paid_at`, `payment_in_id` (FK to `payments_in`). This table is the single source of truth for the payment reminder Edge Functions and the Buyer Portal payment tracker. It is auto-generated when a reservation is confirmed and the payment plan is agreed.

### 3.4 Missing: Full Overdue Escalation Logic

The PRD defines the reminder sequence (7d, 3d, due date, 3d late, 7d late, 14d late, 30d late) in §5.2.6, but the Edge Functions register only lists `payment-reminder-7d`, `payment-reminder-3d`, and `payment-overdue`. The implementation plan only builds the 7d and 3d reminders.

> **Corrected Requirement:** The `payment-overdue` Edge Function shall implement the full escalation chain: due-date notice, 3-day gentle follow-up, 7-day formal notice, 14-day sales agent escalation (creates a task for the assigned sales agent), and 30-day auto-generation of Notice of Default letter (stored as DRAFT, requires developer approval before sending). Each stage shall be logged with timestamp and delivery status.

### 3.5 Missing: Buyer Authentication Flow

The PRD says buyers access the Buyer Portal but never specifies how they authenticate. Magic link? Password set during reservation? Invited by the system?

> **Corrected Requirement:** When a reservation is confirmed, the system shall create a Supabase Auth account for the buyer using their WhatsApp-registered phone number and email. The buyer receives a magic link via email and a WhatsApp message with a link to set their password. Subsequent logins use email + password. Password reset via magic link. The buyer's role is `buyer` and their RLS policy restricts access to their own reservation, payments, and documents only.

### 3.6 Underspecified: Contractor Authentication

Same issue as buyer auth — the PRD says contractors log into the Contractor Portal but never defines how their accounts are created.

> **Corrected Requirement:** When a contractor is added to the `contractors` table by the developer or site manager, the system shall send an email invitation with a magic link to create credentials. Contractor role is `contractor`. RLS restricts access to: their own invoices, their own payment status, and project progress data for projects they are assigned to. They cannot see budget data, other contractor invoices, or buyer information.

### 3.7 Missing: Currency Handling

The PRD references ₦, GBP, and USD throughout (diaspora pricing, Stripe for international billing) but never defines whether the system stores amounts in multiple currencies or converts.

> **Corrected Requirement:** All financial amounts in the database shall be stored in Nigerian Naira (₦) as the canonical currency. All `amount` columns are BIGINT representing kobo (smallest unit). The frontend shall display ₦ amounts natively and, for diaspora-facing views (landing page, WhatsApp messages), shall display an approximate equivalent in GBP/USD using a daily exchange rate stored in a `config` table. Exchange rates are informational only — all contracts and payments are denominated in ₦.

### 3.8 Naming Inconsistency: OpenClaw References

The PRD's prose sections (§8.3, §9, Appendix B) still reference "OpenClaw" in places where they clearly mean "DEVOS Agent Engine." The Edge Functions register says "call OpenClaw PRESELL Agent." The Appendix B team table says "OpenClaw agent configuration." This contradicts the PRD's own explicit distinction in §4.1 and §5.6.

> **Corrected Requirement:** A global find-and-replace must be performed on both the PRD and Implementation Plan. Every reference to "OpenClaw" that describes a DEVOS product function must be changed to "DEVOS Agent Engine" or the specific agent name (e.g., "DEVOS PRESELL Agent"). OpenClaw should only appear in the §5.6 relationship definition and the morning brief flow where Law's personal tool reads DEVOS data.

### 3.9 Missing: 2FA Implementation

PRD §10.1 states "Developer account protected with mandatory 2FA" but provides no specification.

> **Corrected Requirement:** Users with role `org_admin` (developer) shall be required to enable TOTP-based 2FA (via Supabase Auth MFA) on first login. Login without 2FA shall be blocked after a 7-day grace period. Super admins shall always require 2FA with no grace period.

### 3.10 Missing: Feature Flags and Org Impersonation

PRD §5.5 lists "Feature flags per organisation" and "Impersonate organisation (read-only)" as Super Admin capabilities. Neither is defined.

> **Corrected Requirement:** A `feature_flags` table shall exist with columns: `organisation_id`, `flag_name` (enum), `enabled` (boolean), `updated_by`, `updated_at`. Flags control access to modules (e.g., GUARDIAN, AdEngine) and experimental features. The Super Admin panel shall include an "Impersonate" button per org that sets a read-only session context showing that org's dashboard, leads, and data without write permissions. All impersonation sessions are logged.

